		<!-- Begin Comments -->
		
		<b>Comment By David Weber, 6-22-05</b>
		<p>I think you missed the point of Bike to Work day...by a long shot. I stopped at the breakfast station hosted by the Colorado Group at 47th and Colorado, enjoying a few snacks, good company and a chair massage. I ride my bike by this same spot everyday on my way to work, so it was a nice surprise to stop today and be rewarded for commuting in something other than a car. Your view of "everyone happily riding bikes and freeloading together on one day a year," is so absurd that I think you may be pulling everyone's leg. Am I right?<br />
<br />
David Weber</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 6-22-05</b>
		<p>Yep, I'm guilty of leg-pulling--I was hoping my tone would indicate that, but I'll clarify just in case.  I thought it was interesting that certain breakfast stations have built reputations among cyclists who participate every year, and I found it amusing that some people I spoke to were let down when they compared this year's breakfast to previous experiences, because, after all, it's a free, fun, community building event.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Courtney Lowery, 6-22-05</b>
		<p>Jenny, I clearly saw your tongue in your cheek. Thank you for putting it there. I got one hell of a good laugh out of it. Great piece.</p>
		
